         <abstract>
            <p>An examination is made of a sample of 56 public utility bonds refunded prior to scheduled maturity. The present value of the net cash flows resulting from each refunding is calculated and examined. Although the majority of the refundings in the sample appear to have produced favorable cash flow results when viewed from an historical perspective, a number of the refunding decisions appear questionable when viewed solely in light of the information available at the time.</p>
         </abstract>
